column37: Just 1-13 over fences but comes here after two good recent runs, the latter when a clear second at Uttoxeter (3m, good); still on a workable mark and will be suited by the extra distance today; respected.

column37: Useful handicapper in his prime; seemingly back in good nick when easily winning a point in March but struggled in a Cartmel hunter chase in May and now has it all to prove again.

column37: Reportedly aided by refitted tongue-tie when causing 40-1 shock at Ffos Las (3m, good to soft) last November but has not yet built on that performance and he's not easy to predict on this first start for five months.

column37: 5-15 over fences; looked as good as ever when placed at Perth (3m, good) last month, after a break, and was runner-up on his only visit to Chepstow; likely contender.

column37: In good form at Newton Abbot in early part of this season (3m2f, winner on good ground) and had an excuse when pulled up at Stratford last month (sustained a wound) but this is more competitive than the races he usually contests.

column37: Running well since the spring, most recently second of four at Fontwell (3m2f, good to soft) in first-time visor last month; will probably find others too strong in this deeper race, though; usual cheekpieces refitted.

column37: Twice finished 12th at Cheltenham after a winning her bumper debut at Sedgefield, last time finishing upsides Freddiemissmolli when giving that one 4lb; the hood fitted that day is left off for this hurdling introduction; shouldn't be far away.

column37: Irish point winner; two notable runs in bumpers when fourth at Cheltenham and second at Warwick (winner went on to be second in a Grade 2 at Aintree); she faced a stiff task on her debut over hurdles and, after a disappointing second attempt, returned from a wind operation to finish second behind an unexposed mare at Market Rasen; returns to further; solid chance.

column37: Only 1-7 in Irish points and the balance of her form doesn't look at all strong; best watched.

column4: Tom Malone Bloodstock Novices' Chase (Listed Race) (For The Robert Mottram Memorial Trophy) (GBB)

column36: Not quite a Grade 1 horse over hurdles but twice successful in Grade 2s; chase debut
column37: Not quite a Grade 1 horse over hurdles but twice successful in Grade 2s, the latest occasion when making most at Sandown in April (2m5f, good); could take high rank in the novice chasing scene and drying conditions here will be right up his alley; hard to beat with a fluent round of jumping.

column36: Useful handicapper over hurdles, excelling at 3m; won on chase debut; 2m too tight latest
column37: Not in Blueking d'Oroux's league over hurdles but a smart handicapper on his day, particularly once stepped up to 3m; got away with 2m4f when beating two inferior rivals on his chase debut in May but couldn't cope with 2m when last of the four in a handicap at Worcester; at least back over further here and he might be the one should the favourite fluff his lines.

column37: Dual hurdle winner but kept very different company in that scene to the best of today's opposition and she was last of the three runners when odds-on for chase debut at Ludlow in May (2m4f, good); unlikely to be good enough.

column36: A winner over fences but relying on the top two on the racecard being below their best
column37: Has plenty to find on hurdle form and this mare failed to build on her beginners' chase win at Down Royal when 9l off the winner at Listowel (2m3f, yielding); she's relying on the top two on the racecard being below their best.

column36: Did very well to finish third on handicap debut at Aintree festival; major player here
column37: A very useful novice hurdler last season and ran big race when third of 17 on handicap debut at Aintree festival (2m, good) in April, having been badly hampered in early stages and made up considerable ground from the rear; 5lb higher here but still has more to offer.

column37: Well handicapped on best form for Nicky Henderson but became inconsistent for that stable and changed hands after midfield finish at Cheltenham Festival in March; usually runs over 2m4f+; best watched on stable debut.

column37: Returned to form with win at Ayr (2m, good to soft) in April and bettered that performance when commendable second of 17 at Punchestown festival (2m, yielding) later that month; not yet fully exposed after only nine hurdle runs; contender if still in same form after summer break.

column37: Battled gamely to collect a good prize at Windsor (3m, soft) in January and is now 3-9 over hurdles; may still have more improvement to come at some stage but this drop back to 2m is not an obvious move.

column36: Listed novice winner; flopped when upped to 2m4f for h'cap debut but remains of interest
column37: Useful in bumpers before launching hurdling career with three 2m wins (one at Listed level) last autumn; seemed to have her limitations exposed afterwards and finished well down the field when upped to 2m4f for handicap debut at Aintree festival in April but could quite plausibly have some improvement to come this year.

column37: 3-14 over hurdles; ran well at Cheltenham (2m1f, good) in April on latest outing, despite fading into sixth of 16, and begins this new campaign from a workable mark; each-way claims at least.

column36: Did well for new stable last year; needs to squeeze out more improvement to bag this prize
column37: Did well for new stable in 2024, winning twice, and runner-up in valuable Southwell handicap (2m, good) on New Year's Day; reverts to hurdling after a pipe-opener on the Flat last month; probably needs to squeeze out even more improvement to land this prize.

column36: Won five times last season but signed off with poor run in March; others preferred
column37: Won five times during a very productive campaign last season but signed off with a disappointing run in series final at Kelso in March and needs a career-best performance to have any chance here.

column36: Largely in good form in run-of-the-mill handicaps since spring; this is a big ask, though
column37: Largely in good form in run-of-the-mill handicaps since the spring (two wins) and lost out only narrowly at Worcester (2m, good) last month to a progressive subsequent winner; faces daunting task from 5lb out of the weights in this much stronger race, though.

column4: DragonBet John Ayres Memorial Handicap Chase (GBB Race)
column19: Dan Skelton runs five and his jockey bookings suggest a big run is likely from JET PLANE, who did well in hunter chases last season.

column36: Fine second in Grand Annual at Cheltenham in March but overlooked by Harry Skelton today
column37: Won Grand Annual Chase at 2024 Cheltenham Festival (2m, soft) and an honourable second in this year's edition of that race; also suited by this C&D but makes seasonal debut from career-high mark and Harry Skelton evidently prefers Jet Plane today.
